</paragraph>
<paragraph id="DE68690C019CF275AF555269C5724EF4" pageId="32" pageNumber="33">Afrotropical region (excluding Madagascar) and Arabian Peninsula (?) (Fig. 317).</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="A3007101E0A55CD3F1D660448A6A66D8" pageId="32" pageNumber="33" type="ecology">
<paragraph id="D06DC8F6BC0D77323686EEA268069C60" pageId="32" pageNumber="33">Ecology.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="833CDE3D3E787A3E05AF1F44F10B843C" pageId="32" pageNumber="33">
Polyphagous. This genus has been associated with several plant families (cf. 
<bibRefCitation id="50B8D9F27B4522ECC7645E6BAFD3546C" author="Jolivet, P" journalOrPublisher="An essay about the relationships between the leaf-beetles and their food-plants. Backhuys Publishers, Leiden" pageId="52" pageNumber="53" title="Host-plants of Chrysomelidae of the World." year="1995">Jolivet and Hawkeswood 1995</bibRefCitation>
; personal data).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="FF4CD9F72E610C696D13D09EF0FBB5A1" pageId="32" pageNumber="33" type="notes">
<paragraph id="4E8BA2C9D30DBC34ED54FFC2CF80F535" pageId="32" pageNumber="33">Notes.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="23FBA72036920D3486E5448CC753E4BA" pageId="32" pageNumber="33">
About one hundred and fifty species are known to occur in Sub-Saharan Africa. According to 
<bibRefCitation id="B18B82696BF6E6F6FFDCA9435360F415" author="Biondi, M" journalOrPublisher="Italian Journal of Zoology" pageId="48" pageNumber="49" title="Drakensbergianella rudebecki, new genus and new species from the mountains of the Southern Africa, and taxonomic observations on Gabonia Jacoby and related genera (Coleoptera: Chrysomelidae, Alticinae). Zoologischer Anzeiger 242: 97 − 106." url="10.1078/0044-5231-00090" year="2003">
Biondi and 
<normalizedToken id="4CE1F9DBD28EECAB95A84D0806928FEB" originalValue="D’Alessandro">D'Alessandro</normalizedToken>
(2003)
</bibRefCitation>
, 
<taxonomicName id="6ABF431645976DF4560E42D65C0A5337" authority="Jacoby, 1893" authorityName="Jacoby" authorityYear="1893" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Gabonia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Gabonia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="32" pageNumber="33" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Gabonia</taxonomicName>
is closely related to 
<taxonomicName id="DD8F21BCB9C519F295AA3D497B1A2862" authority="Weise, 1887" authorityName="Weise" authorityYear="1887" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Luperomorpha" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Luperomorpha" order="Coleoptera" pageId="32" pageNumber="33" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Luperomorpha</taxonomicName>
Weise, 1887. The latter genus is widespread and prevalent in the Australian and Oriental regions, and is probably a synonym of the former genus. Many species currently attributed to 
<taxonomicName id="C3FF8208D7475F71CB0618715A222803" authority="Jacoby, 1893" authorityName="Jacoby" authorityYear="1893" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Gabonia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Gabonia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="32" pageNumber="33" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Gabonia</taxonomicName>
do not show any significant differences from 
<taxonomicName id="E3645A882EDBD93544A2D209B0551B25" authority="Weise, 1887" authorityName="Weise" authorityYear="1887" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Luperomorpha" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Luperomorpha" order="Coleoptera" pageId="32" pageNumber="33" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Luperomorpha</taxonomicName>
species. The diagnostic character reported by 
<bibRefCitation id="8E636048D6A81EDE9A5DFA15A4D12175" pageId="32" pageNumber="33">
Scherer and 
<normalizedToken id="4928BAC4B3EEC7E4067026762BC0B21B" originalValue="Boppré">Boppre</normalizedToken>
(1997)
</bibRefCitation>
for separating these two genera is the apical spur on the hind tibia: long and straight in 
<taxonomicName id="DE9E93426CA0B5942EE3EEA49A61BBD7" authority="Jacoby, 1893" authorityName="Jacoby" authorityYear="1893" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Gabonia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Gabonia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="32" pageNumber="33" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Gabonia</taxonomicName>
; very short in 
<taxonomicName id="FB1B08A7BCDEC7CF2047BBD7A9ADEC94" authority="Weise, 1887" authorityName="Weise" authorityYear="1887" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Luperomorpha" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Luperomorpha" order="Coleoptera" pageId="32" pageNumber="33" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Luperomorpha</taxonomicName>
. However, this character is not always reliable. In view of the wide spectrum of variability displayed by the genus 
<taxonomicName id="005B0FEFF0ED9127DCD75D494EE2FA19" authority="Jacoby, 1893" authorityName="Jacoby" authorityYear="1893" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Gabonia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Gabonia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="32" pageNumber="33" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Gabonia</taxonomicName>
, and the need to consider various other genera, synonymy with 
<taxonomicName id="5F290FD06D10AB3DD1245DC50FD0A14A" authority="Weise, 1887" authorityName="Weise" authorityYear="1887" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Luperomorpha" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Luperomorpha" order="Coleoptera" pageId="32" pageNumber="33" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Luperomorpha</taxonomicName>
may be confirmed by a detailed and careful comparative study of this complicated African genus in the future (
<bibRefCitation id="C715B7F8C074A8BFE43A124D1F78C46D" pageId="32" pageNumber="33">
Biondi and 
<normalizedToken id="264424E2B3AED018BAA82DD742C3CC7B" originalValue="D’Alessandro">D'Alessandro</normalizedToken>
2010a
</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation id="F1AD64A34D59AB74B70DED7E440BE3A1" pageId="32" pageNumber="33">Doguet 1979</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
